dom-geolocation-watchposition.name: watchPosition
dom-geolocation-watchposition.summary: The Geolocation method watchPosition() method is used to register a handler function that will be called automatically each time the position of the device changes.
dom-geolocation-watchposition.title: Geolocation.watchPosition()

geolocation_interface.name: Geolocation
geolocation_interface.summary: The Geolocation interface represents an object able to programmatically obtain the position of the device. It gives Web content access to the location of the device. This allows a Web site or app to offer customized results based on the user's location.

firefox.notes: GPSD (GPS daemon) support added in Firefox 3.6. WiFi-based location is provided by Google (privacy) or a custom provider (MLS instructions).

geolocation_interface.title: Geolocation

dom-geolocationcoordinates-accuracy.name: accuracy
dom-geolocationcoordinates-accuracy.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.accuracy read-only property is a strictly positive double representing the accuracy, with a 95% confidence level, of the GeolocationCoordinates.latitude and GeolocationCoordinates.longitude properties expressed in meters.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-accuracy.title: GeolocationCoordinates.accuracy

dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitude.name: altitude
dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitude.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.altitude read-only property is a double representing the altitude of the position in meters, relative to sea level. This value is null if the implementation cannot provide this data.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitude.title: GeolocationCoordinates.altitude

dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitudeaccur.name: altitudeAccuracy
dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitudeaccur.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.altitudeAccuracy read-only property is a strictly positive double representing the accuracy, with a 95% confidence level, of the altitude expressed in meters. This value is null if the implementation doesn't support measuring altitude.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-altitudeaccur.title: GeolocationCoordinates.altitudeAccuracy

dom-geolocationcoordinates-heading.name: heading
dom-geolocationcoordinates-heading.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.heading read-only property is a double representing the direction in which the device is traveling. This value, specified in degrees, indicates how far off from heading due north the device is. Zero degrees represents true true north, and the direction is determined clockwise (which means that east is 90 degrees and west is 270 degrees). If GeolocationCoordinates.speed is 0, heading is NaN. If the device is not able to provide heading information, this value is null.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-heading.title: GeolocationCoordinates.heading

dom-geolocationcoordinates-latitude.name: latitude
dom-geolocationcoordinates-latitude.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.latitude read-only property is a double representing the latitude of the position in decimal degrees.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-latitude.title: GeolocationCoordinates.latitude

dom-geolocationcoordinates-longitude.name: longitude
dom-geolocationcoordinates-longitude.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates interface's read-only longitude property is a double-precision floating point value which represents the longitude of a geographical position, specified in decimal degrees. Together with a DOMTimeStamp indicating a time of measurement, the GeolocationCoordinates object is part of the GeolocationPosition interface, which is the object type returned by Geolocation API functions that obtain and return a geographical position.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-longitude.title: GeolocationCoordinates.longitude

dom-geolocationcoordinates-speed.name: speed
dom-geolocationcoordinates-speed.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates.speed read-only property is a double representing the velocity of the device in meters per second. This value is null if the implementation is not able to measure it.
dom-geolocationcoordinates-speed.title: GeolocationCoordinates.speed

coordinates_interface.name: GeolocationCoordinates
coordinates_interface.summary: The GeolocationCoordinates interface represents the position and altitude of the device on Earth, as well as the accuracy with which these properties are calculated.
coordinates_interface.title: GeolocationCoordinates

dom-geolocationposition-coords.name: coords
dom-geolocationposition-coords.summary: The GeolocationPosition.coords read-only property returns a GeolocationCoordinates object representing a geographic position. It contains the location, that is longitude and latitude on the Earth, the altitude, and the speed of the object concerned, regrouped inside the returned value. It also contains accuracy information about these values.
dom-geolocationposition-coords.title: GeolocationPosition.coords

dom-geolocationposition-timestamp.name: timestamp
dom-geolocationposition-timestamp.summary: The GeolocationPosition.timestamp read-only property returns a DOMTimeStamp object, represents the date and the time of the creation of the GeolocationPosition object it belongs to. The precision is to the millisecond.
dom-geolocationposition-timestamp.title: GeolocationPosition.timestamp

position_interface.name: GeolocationPosition
position_interface.summary: The GeolocationPosition interface represents the position of the concerned device at a given time. The position, represented by a GeolocationCoordinates object, comprehends the 2D position of the device, on a spheroid representing the Earth, but also its altitude and its speed.
position_interface.title: GeolocationPosition

dom-geolocationpositionerror-code.name: code
dom-geolocationpositionerror-code.summary: The GeolocationPositionError.code read-only property is an unsigned short representing the error code.
dom-geolocationpositionerror-code.title: GeolocationPositionError.code

dom-geolocationpositionerror-message.name: message
dom-geolocationpositionerror-message.summary: The GeolocationPositionError.message read-only property returns a human-readable DOMString describing the details of the error.
dom-geolocationpositionerror-message.title: GeolocationPositionError.message

position_error_interface.name: GeolocationPositionError
position_error_interface.summary: The GeolocationPositionError interface represents the reason of an error occurring when using the geolocating device.
position_error_interface.title: GeolocationPositionError

dom-navigator-geolocation.name: geolocation
dom-navigator-geolocation.summary: The Navigator.geolocation read-only property returns a Geolocation object that gives Web content access to the location of the device. This allows a Web site or app to offer customized results based on the user's location.
dom-navigator-geolocation.title: Navigator.geolocation

dom-positionoptions-enablehighaccuracy.name: enableHighAccuracy
dom-positionoptions-enablehighaccuracy.summary: The PositionOptions.enableHighAccuracy property is a Boolean that indicates the application would like to receive the best possible results. If true and if the device is able to provide a more accurate position, it will do so. Note that this can result in slower response times or increased power consumption (with a GPS chip on a mobile device for example). On the other hand, if false (the default value), the device can take the liberty to save resources by responding more quickly and/or using less power.
dom-positionoptions-enablehighaccuracy.title: PositionOptions.enableHighAccuracy

dom-positionoptions-maximumage.name: maximumAge
dom-positionoptions-maximumage.summary: The PositionOptions.maximumAge property is a positive long value indicating the maximum age in milliseconds of a possible cached position that is acceptable to return. If set to 0, it means that the device cannot use a cached position and must attempt to retrieve the real current position. If set to Infinity the device must return a cached position regardless of its age.
dom-positionoptions-maximumage.title: PositionOptions.maximumAge

dom-positionoptions-timeout.name: timeout
dom-positionoptions-timeout.summary: The PositionOptions.timeout property is a positive long value representing the maximum length of time (in milliseconds) the device is allowed to take in order to return a position. The default value is Infinity, meaning that getCurrentPosition() won't return until the position is available.
dom-positionoptions-timeout.title: PositionOptions.timeout

position_options_interface.name: PositionOptions
position_options_interface.summary: The PositionOptions dictionary describes an object containing option properties to pass as a parameter of Geolocation.getCurrentPosition() and Geolocation.watchPosition().
position_options_interface.title: PositionOptions
